,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":198,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYZ4qvvMQkzZSCPG4LX1u\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"66f74dad-811d-49e6-98c2-cf971c9c813e\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-27T18:43:40.338Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"66f74dad-811d-49e6-98c2-cf971c9c813e\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"571d4d62-7976-4f0c-a786-39c327a25b6e\",\"version\":\"2.1.62\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/kiro-oneshot\",\"slug\":\"eager-wondering-bubble\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"PostToolUse\",\"hookName\":\"PostToolUse:Read\",\"command\":\"callback\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01YaK2WvR8oUiPForzwReyqP\",\"toolUseID\":\"toolu_01YaK2WvR8oUiPForzwReyqP\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-27T18:43:40.348Z\",\"uuid\":\"b6337f1a-be76-493a-a368-bf42c052cecf\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"66f74dad-811d-49e6-98c2-cf971c9c813e\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"571d4d62-7976-4f0c-a786-39c327a25b6e\",\"version\":\"2.1.62\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/kiro-oneshot\",\"slug\":\"eager-wondering-bubble\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01YaK2WvR8oUiPForzwReyqP\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Implement Command\\n     2→\\n     3→Build the agent Go package using strict E2E-first TDD. Unit tests are written ONLY after all E2E tests pass.\\n     4→\\n     5→## Prerequisites\\n     6→\\n     7→- The research command's one-pager at `cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_PACKAGE/AGENT.md`\\n     8→- The E2E test runner already added (from `write-tests` command)\\n     9→- If no one-pager exists, read the agent's docs and ask the user about hook events, transcript format, and config\\n    10→\\n    11→## Core Principle: E2E-First TDD\\n    12→\\n    13→1. **E2E tests are the spec.** The existing `ForEachAgent` test scenarios define \\\"working\\\". You implement until they pass.\\n    14→2. **Watch it fail first.** Every E2E tier starts by running the test and observing the failure. If you haven't seen the failure, you don't understand what needs fixing.\\n    15→3. **Minimum viable fix.** At each failure, implement only the code needed to make that specific assertion pass. Don't anticipate future tiers.\\n    16→4. **`/debug-e2e` is your debugger.** When an E2E test fails, use the artifact directory with `/debug-e2e` before guessing at fixes.\\n    17→5. **No unit tests during Steps 4-12.** Unit tests are written in Step 13 after all E2E tiers pass, using real data from E2E runs as golden fixtures.\\n    18→6. **Format and lint, don't unit test.** Between E2E tiers, run `mise run fmt && mise run lint` to keep code clean. No `mise run test` until Step 13.\\n    19→7. **If you didn't watch it fail, you don't know if it tests the right thing.**\\n    20→\\n    21→**Do NOT write unit tests during Steps 4-12.** All test writing is consolidated in Step 13.\\n    22→\\n    23→## Procedure\\n    24→\\n    25→### Step 1: Read Implementation Guide\\n    26→\\n    27→Read these files thoroughly before writing any code:\\n    28→\\n    29→1. `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` — Authoritative implementation guide with code templates. Read thoroughly.\\n    30→2. `docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md` — Validation criteria for completeness.\\n    31→3. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` — Read to find the exact `Agent` interface and all optional interfaces.\\n    32→4. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` — Read to find `EventType` constants and shared parsing helpers.\\n    33→\\n    34→### Step 2: Read Reference Implementation\\n    35→\\n    36→Read `cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_PACKAGE/AGENT.md` (the one-pager from the research phase) for the agent's hook mechanism, transcript format, and config structure.\\n    37→\\n    38→Run `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/\\\")` to find all existing agent packages. Check the one-pager's \\\"Hook Mechanism\\\" and \\\"Gaps & Limitations\\\" sections to pick the best reference — choose an agent with a similar hook mechanism to your target. Read all `*.go` files (skip `*_test.go` on first pass) in the chosen reference.\\n    39→\\n    40→### Step 3: Create Bare-Minimum Compiling Package\\n    41→\\n    42→Create the agent package directory and stub out every required interface method so the project compiles.\\n    43→\\n    44→```\\n    45→cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_PACKAGE/\\n    46→```\\n    47→\\n    48→**What to create:**\\n    49→\\n    50→1. **`${AGENT_PACKAGE}.go`** — Struct definition, `init()` with `agent.Register(agent.AgentName(\\\"$AGENT_KEY\\\"), New)`, and stub implementations for every method in the `Agent` interface — refer to `agent.go` from Step 1. Include `HookSupport` methods in `lifecycle.go` and `hooks.go`.\\n    51→2. **`types.go`** — Hook input struct(s) with JSON tags matching the one-pager's \\\"Hook input (stdin JSON)\\\" section.\\n    52→3. **`lifecycle.go`** — Stub `ParseHookEvent()` that returns `nil, nil` for all inputs. Use the one-pager's \\\"Hook names\\\" table for the native hook name → Entire EventType mapping.\\n    53→4. **`hooks.go`** — Stub `InstallHooks()`, `UninstallHooks()`, `AreHooksInstalled()` that return nil/false. Use the one-pager's \\\"Config file\\\" and \\\"Hook registration\\\" sections for the config path and format.\\n    54→5. **`transcript.go`** — Stub `TranscriptAnalyzer` methods if the one-pager's \\\"Transcript\\\" section indicates the agent supports transcript analysis. Use the one-pager for transcript location and format.\\n    55→\\n    56→**Wire up blank imports:**\\n    57→\\n    58→- Ensure the blank import `_ \\\"github.com/entireio/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_PACKAGE\\\"` exists in `cmd/entire/cli/hooks_cmd.go`\\n    59→\\n    60→**Verify compilation:**\\n    61→\\n    62→```bash\\n    63→mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test\\n    64→```\\n    65→\\n    66→Everything must pass before proceeding. Fix any issues.\\n    67→\\n    68→**Standing instruction for Steps 4-12:** If you need agent-specific information (hook format, transcript location, config structure), check `AGENT.md` first. If `AGENT.md` doesn't cover what you need, you may search external docs — but always update `AGENT.md` with anything new you discover so future steps don't need to re-search.\\n    69→\\n    70→### Step 4: E2E Tier 1 — `TestHumanOnlyChangesAndCommits`\\n    71→\\n    72→This test requires no agent prompts — it only exercises hooks, so it's the fastest feedback loop.\\n    73→\\n    74→**What it exercises:**\\n    75→- `InstallHooks()` — real hook installation in the agent's config\\n    76→- `AreHooksInstalled()` — detection that hooks are present\\n    77→- `ParseHookEvent()` — at minimum, the event types needed for session start and turn end (see `EventType` constants in `event.go`)\\n    78→- Basic hook invocation flow (the test calls hooks directly via the CLI)\\n    79→\\n    80→**Cycle:**\\n    81→\\n    82→1. Run: `mise run test:e2e:$AGENT_SLUG TestHumanOnlyChangesAndCommits`\\n    83→2. **Watch it fail** — read the failure output carefully\\n    84→3. If there are artifact dirs, use `/debug-e2e {artifact-dir}` to understand what happened\\n    85→4. Implement the minimum code to fix the first failure\\n    86→5. Repeat until the test passes\\n    87→\\n    88→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint`\\n    89→\\n    90→### Step 5: E2E Tier 2 — `TestSingleSessionManualCommit`\\n    91→\\n    92→The foundational test. This exercises the full agent lifecycle: start session → agent prompt → agent produces files → user commits → session ends.\\n    93→\\n    94→**What it exercises:**\\n    95→- Complete `ParseHookEvent()` for all lifecycle event types from `event.go`. Use the one-pager's hook mapping table to translate native hook names to `EventType` constants.\\n    96→- `GetSessionDir` / `ResolveSessionFile` — finding the agent's session/transcript files\\n    97→- `ReadTranscript` / `ChunkTranscript` / `ReassembleTranscript` — reading native transcript format\\n    98→- `TranscriptAnalyzer` methods (see `agent.go` for current method signatures)\\n    99→\\n   100→**Cycle:**\\n   101→\\n   102→1. Run: `mise run test:e2e:$AGENT_SLUG TestSingleSessionManualCommit`\\n   103→2. **Watch it fail** — read the failure output carefully\\n   104→3. Use `/debug-e2e {artifact-dir}` to understand what happened\\n   105→4. Implement the minimum code to fix the first failure\\n   106→5. Repeat until the test passes\\n   107→\\n   108→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint`\\n   109→\\n   110→### Step 6: E2E Tier 2b — `TestCheckpointMetadataDeepValidation`\\n   111→\\n   112→Validates transcript quality: JSONL validity, content hash correctness, prompt extraction accuracy.\\n   113→\\n   114→**What it exercises:**\\n   115→- Transcript content stored at checkpoints is valid JSONL\\n   116→- Content hash matches the stored transcript\\n   117→- User prompts are correctly extracted\\n   118→- Metadata fields are populated\\n   119→\\n   120→**Cycle:**\\n   121→\\n   122→1. Run: `mise run test:e2e:$AGENT_SLUG TestCheckpointMetadataDeepValidation`\\n   123→2. **Watch it fail** — this test often exposes subtle transcript formatting bugs\\n   124→3. Use `/debug-e2e {artifact-dir}` on any failures\\n   125→4. Fix and repeat\\n   126→\\n   127→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint`\\n   128→\\n   129→### Step 7: E2E Tier 3 — `TestSingleSessionAgentCommitInTurn`\\n   130→\\n   131→Agent creates files and commits them within a single prompt turn. Tests the in-turn commit path.\\n   132→\\n   133→**What it exercises:**\\n   134→- Hook events firing during an agent's commit (post-commit hooks while agent is active)\\n   135→- Checkpoint creation when agent commits mid-turn\\n   136→- Usually no new agent-specific code needed — this tests the strategy's handling of agent commits\\n   137→\\n   138→**Cycle:**\\n   139→\\n   140→1. Run: `mise run test:e2e:$AGENT_SLUG TestSingleSessionAgentCommitInTurn`\\n   141→2. **Watch it fail** — use `/debug-e2e {artifact-dir}` on failures\\n   142→3. Fix and repeat — if the agent doesn't support committing, skip this test\\n   143→\\n   144→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint`\\n   145→\\n   146→### Step 8: E2E Tier 4 — Multi-Session Tests\\n   147→\\n   148→Run these tests to validate multi-session behavior:\\n   149→\\n   150→- `TestMultiSessionManualCommit` — Two sessions, both produce files, user commits\\n   151→- `TestMultiSessionSequential` — Sessions run one after another\\n   152→- `TestEndedSessionUserCommitsAfterExit` — User commits after session ends\\n   153→\\n   154→**Cycle (for each test):**\\n   155→\\n   156→1. Run: `mise run test:e2e:$AGENT_SLUG TestMultiSessionManualCommit`\\n   157→2. **Watch it fail** — use `/debug-e2e {artifact-dir}` on failures\\n   158→3. Fix and repeat\\n   159→4. Move to next test\\n   160→\\n   161→These tests rarely need new agent code — they exercise the strategy layer.\\n   162→\\n   163→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint`\\n   164→\\n   165→### Step 9: E2E Tier 5 — File Operation Edge Cases\\n   166→\\n   167→Run these tests for file operation correctness:\\n   168→\\n   169→- `TestModifyExistingTrackedFile` — Agent modifies (not creates) a file\\n   170→- `TestUserSplitsAgentChanges` — User stages only some of the agent's changes\\n   171→- `TestDeletedFilesCommitDeletion` — Agent deletes a file, user commits the deletion\\n   172→- `TestMixedNewAndModifiedFiles` — Agent both creates and modifies files\\n   173→\\n   174→**Cycle:** Same as above — run each test, **watch it fail**, use `/debug-e2e` on failures, fix, repeat.\\n   175→\\n   176→Run: `mise run fmt && mise run lint`\\n   177→\\n   178→### Step 10: Optional Interfaces\\n   179→\\n   180→Read `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent